    <string name="what_does_this_scan_actually_measure">What does this scan actually measure?</string>
    <string name="what_should_i_do_with_the_result">What should I do with the result?</string>
    <string name="ans_1_hrv">Run it when you feel mentally tense, overwhelmed, wired, or unusually low on energy — even if nothing obvious happened. It’s especially useful before a big meeting, after a stressful moment, or at the end of a long day.</string>
    <string name="ans_2_hrv">This scan compares your current Heart Rate Variability to your personal baseline. HRV reflects how balanced your nervous system is right now — whether your body is in a calm, adaptable state or under strain.</string>
    <string name="ans_3_hrv">If your state is balanced or thriving, it’s a good time for focus or training. If it’s strained or overloaded, consider short recovery actions — breathing exercises, hydration, a short walk, or reducing mental load.</string>
    <string name="start_scan">Start Scan</string>
    <string name="average_data_message">We’re still gathering data to establish your average %1$s.</string>
    <string name="baseline_ready_message">Please wear the device continuously over the next few days. This allows us to gather sufficient data to establish your %1$s baseline accurately.\n\nYou’ll receive a notification once your baseline is ready, and you can start your %2$s check.</string>
    <string name="your_usual_oxygen_level">Your usual Oxygen Level</string>
    <string name="usual_spo2">Usual SPO2</string>
    <string name="ready_for_your_stress_check">Ready for Your Stress Check?</string>
    <string name="check_your_body_load">Check Your Body Load</string>
    <string name="oxygen_level_check">Oxygen Level Check</string>
    <string name="thermal_check">Thermal Check</string>
    <string name="ans_1_hr">Use this when you feel physically tired, wired, or “off” — especially if you\'re resting but feel your body is still working hard. It\'s helpful during afternoon slumps or before winding down for sleep.</string>
    <string name="ans_2_hr">It compares your current heart rate to your usual resting level. If your heart rate is higher than expected while inactive, your body may be under hidden physical strain.</string>
    <string name="ans_3_hr">If your load is elevated, consider hydration, light movement, posture reset, or avoiding stimulants. If it’s stable, your body is recovering as expected.</string>
    <string name="ans_1_sop2">Use this if you feel foggy, low on energy, sluggish, or after being indoors for long periods. It can also be helpful after travel or poor sleep.</string>
    <string name="ans_2_sop2">It compares your current oxygen saturation to your personal normal range. Even small dips can influence how alert or energised you feel.</string>
    <string name="ans_3_sop2">If levels are slightly below your usual range, try deep breathing, improving posture, or stepping into fresh air. If normal, your energy dip may be linked to other factors like stress or sleep.</string>
    <string name="ans_1_thermal">Use this if you feel unusually warm, restless before sleep, fatigued after workouts, or slightly “off” without clear reason.</string>
    <string name="ans_2_thermal">It compares your current skin temperature to your personal circadian baseline. Small deviations can signal recovery strain, environmental stress, or rhythm disruption.</string>
    <string name="ans_3_thermal">If temperature is elevated, focus on cooling strategies — lower room temperature, hydration, light activity, or earlier wind-down before bed.</string>
